<article>
    <h1>5 ways to re&#xAD;ju&#xAD;ve&#xAD;nate re&#xAD;tail</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-09"><time>2021-01-09</time></a>
        - <span>DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline">Robin&#xAD;sons&#x2019; 186,000 sq ft flag&#xAD;ship Heeren out&#xAD;let (left) closed on&#xD;&#xA;Dec 16. ST PHOTO: DESMOND WEE</span>
    </section>

    <p>Bricks-and-mor­tar spa­ces play a crit­i­cal role in build­ing a re­tail store brand and form part of a holis­tic ap­proach to en­gag­ing cus­tomers both on­line and off­line.</p>
    <p>Mr Markus Pe­sendor­fer, de­sign di­rec­tor and re­gional brand and re­tail ex­pe­ri­ence prac­tice leader at de­sign and ar­chi­tec­tural firm Gensler’s Sin­ga­pore of­fice, says there are five ways to boost in-store of­fer­ings.</p>
    <p>1 Pur­pose of place:</p>
    <p>To­day’s con­sumer is driven by a brand’s pur­pose and be­liefs more than the prod­uct or ser­vice it­self.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing to multi­na­tional pro­fes­sional ser­vices com­pany Ac­cen­ture, al­most 63 per cent of global con­sumers pre­fer to buy from com­pa­nies that stand for a pur­pose which re­flects their own val­ues and be­liefs. Re­tail stores that build com­mu­ni­ties through their phys­i­cal spa­ces play a crit­i­cal role in con­nect­ing with cus­tomers.</p>
    <p>2 From trans­ac­tion hub to cul­ture hub:</p>
    <p>Re­tail brands that want to en­gage visi­tors be­yond the tra­di­tional shop­ping ex­pe­ri­ence should of­fer year-round, day-to-night pro­grammes of sea­sonal and sig­na­ture events, says Mr Pe­sendor­fer.</p>
    <p>These cre­ative public ac­tiv­i­ties gal­vanise re­la­tion­ships with cus­tomers and the com­mu­nity. Re­tail en­gage­ment forms the “glue” be­tween the var­i­ous brand seg­ments and, over time, de­vel­ops into a strong brand cul­ture.</p>
    <p>3 Think lo­cal, act lo­cal:</p>
    <p>It is es­sen­tial to be laser-fo­cused on the store’s com­mu­nity and have a fin­ger on the pulse of lo­cal cul­ture.</p>
    <p>Mr Pe­sendor­fer ad­vises cre­at­ing an ex­pe­ri­en­tial ecosys­tem with a cu­rated and unique mix of ten­ants and of­fer­ings that feels specif­i­cally lo­cal to cus­tomers.</p>
    <p>To­day, it is no longer just about shop­ping, he says. It is also about ex­pe­ri­ences that stand out from the com­pe­ti­tion, such as part­ner­ing cre­ative teams that un­der­stand the lo­cal en­vi­ron­ment to cu­rate ex­cit­ing public events.</p>
    <p>4 Pro­mote health and well-be­ing:</p>
    <p>Some shop­ping des­ti­na­tions have al­ready made ef­forts with branded hy­giene and well­ness pro­grammes.</p>
    <p>Health and well-be­ing are up­per­most in peo­ple’s minds, es­pe­cially in an on­go­ing pan­demic. Stores can cre­ate ac­tiv­i­ties cen­tred on food, ex­er­cise, spir­i­tu­al­ity and beauty as a way to pro­mote health­ier life­styles. By sup­port­ing in­tan­gi­bles like these, store man­agers can craft value-added ser­vices for mall visi­tors.</p>
    <p>5 Em­brace the hu­man side of shop­ping:</p>
    <p>While tech­nol­ogy has fun­da­men­tally dis­rupted the tra­di­tional browse-buy cy­cle, shop­pers still want to see, touch and ex­pe­ri­ence mer­chan­dise in per­son.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing to global con­sul­tancy PwC, 75 per cent of con­sumers want more hu­man in­ter­ac­tion in the fu­ture, not less.</p>
    <p>In the fu­ture, cus­tomer loy­alty and suc­cess met­rics will be driven by the level and qual­ity of cus­tomer ser­vice that shop­pers re­ceive, says Mr Pe­sendor­fer.</p>


</article>

